
[1]dive

   DIVE, v.i. [Gr.]

   1. To descend or plunge into water, as an animal head first; to thrust
   the body into water or other liquor, or if already in water, to plunge
   deeper. In the pearl fishery men are employed to dive for shells.

   2. To go deep into any subject; as, to dive into the nature of things,
   into arts or science.

   3. To plunge into any business or condition, so as to be thoroughly
   engaged in it.

   4. To sink; to penetrate.

   Dive, thought, down to my soul.

                  DIVE, v.t. To explore by diving. [Rare.]

   The Curtii bravely dived the gulf of fame.
